{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e313ee68-73ee-4b63-8649-eb821aad9f4e","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is exactly what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — re-installs the workloads you already have **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a new SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after that, verify the MAUI workload is present:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\n```\n\nIf `maui` isn't listed, install it explicitly:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f6ff7e96-07b3-42b2-8edb-3e519c47b895","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general .NET knowledge question — I don't need to search the codebase for this.","outputTokens":268,"requestId":"77CF:311A36:81BA808:8FDE384:69EABDBB"},"id":"15ea51c1-fc8e-4471-8e8b-f36bd5854e17","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:48:03.039Z","parentId":"5fd1f20e-d955-4687-ad98-888d482e25ff"}
